                        <span class="s2">&quot;*&quot;</span><span class="o">:</span> <span class="s2">&quot;{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox comic book title|  &lt;!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--&gt;\n| image = SugarandSpike1.jpg\n| caption = Cover to &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; #1 (April/May 1956)&lt;br&gt;Art by [[Sheldon Mayer]]\n| schedule = Bimonthly\n| format = Standard\n| publisher = [[DC Comics]]\n| date = April/May 1956&amp;ndash;October/November 1971\n| issues = 98\n| main_char_team = Sugar Plumm&lt;br&gt;Cecil \&quot;Spike\&quot; Wilson\n| writers = [[Sheldon Mayer]]\n| artists = Sheldon Mayer\n| pencillers =\n| inkers =\n| colorists =\n| editors = [[Whitney Ellsworth]] #1\u201321&lt;br&gt;[[Lawrence Nadle]] #22\u201352&lt;br&gt;[[Murray Boltinoff]] #53\u201393&lt;br&gt;[[Dick Giordano]] #94&lt;br&gt;[[E. Nelson Bridwell]] #95\u201398\n| creative_team_month =\n| creative_team_year =\n| creators = Sheldon Mayer\n}}\n&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39; is an [[American comic book]] series published by [[DC Comics]] from 1956 through 1971, named after its main protagonists. The series was created, written, and drawn by [[Sheldon Mayer]].\n\n==Publication history==\nThe series was launched in 1956 along with another Sheldon Mayer creation &#39;&#39;[[The Three Mouseketeers]]&#39;&#39;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Irvine|first= Alex|authorlink = Alexander C. Irvine|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1950s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year=2010|location= London, United Kingdom|isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9|page= 81|quote = Two children&#39;s titles began: &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; and &#39;&#39;The Three Mouseketeers&#39;&#39;.}}&lt;/ref&gt; The &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39; series had 98 issues published in the United States through 1971,&lt;ref&gt;{{gcdb series|id= 1195|title= &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39;}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last1= Overstreet|first1= Robert M.|title= [[Overstreet Comic Book Price Guide]]|edition= 49th|publisher= [[Gemstone Publishing]]|date= 2019|location= Timonium, Maryland|pages= 1048\u20131049|isbn= 978-1603602334}}&lt;/ref&gt; when due to Mayer&#39;s failing eyesight that limited his drawing ability, the series was canceled.&lt;ref name=\&quot;Toonopedia\&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url= http://www.toonopedia.com/sh_mayer.htm|title= Sheldon Mayer|last1= Markstein|first1= Don|work= [[Don Markstein&#39;s Toonopedia]]|archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/63e1zyO1w?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/sh_mayer.htm|archivedate= December 3, 2011|quote= He continued to write and draw Sugar &amp; Spike until 1971, when failing eyesight forced him to abandon cartooning...Mayer&#39;s sight was restored a few years later, and he went back to producing new Sugar &amp; Spike stories. But the American comic book market was no longer able to support such a feature, so these were mostly published overseas.|accessdate= December 3, 2011|url-status= live|df= mdy-all}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Later, after [[cataract]] surgery restored his eyesight, Mayer returned to writing and drawing &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; stories, continuing to do so until his death in 1991; these stories appeared in overseas markets&lt;ref name=\&quot;Toonopedia\&quot; /&gt; and only a few have been reprinted in the United States. The American reprints appeared in the [[digest size]]d comics series &#39;&#39;[[The Best of DC]]&#39;&#39; #29, 41, 47, 58, 65, and 68.&lt;ref&gt;Overstreet, pp. 506\u2013507&lt;/ref&gt; In 1992, &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; #99 was published as part of the &#39;&#39;DC Silver Age Classics&#39;&#39; series;&lt;ref&gt;{{gcdb series|id= 17352|title= &#39;&#39;DC Silver Age Classics Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; #99 (1992)}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Overstreet, p. 617&lt;/ref&gt; this featured two previously unpublished stories by Mayer.  DC Comics writer and executive [[Paul Levitz]] has described &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; as being \&quot;Mayer&#39;s most charming and enduring creation\&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|authorlink= Paul Levitz|last=Levitz|first= Paul|title= 75 Years of DC Comics The Art of Modern Mythmaking|publisher= [[Taschen]]|year=2010|location= Cologne, Germany|ISBN= 9783836519816|page= 64}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Novelist and &#39;&#39;[[The Sandman (Vertigo)|Sandman]]&#39;&#39; creator [[Neil Gaiman]] has stated \&quot;Sheldon Mayer&#39;s &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; series...is the most charming thing I&#39;ve ever seen in comics.\&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last = Bender|first = Hy|title = The Sandman Companion|publisher = [[Vertigo (DC Comics)|Vertigo]]|year = 1999|location= New York, New York|page = 154|isbn = 1563894653}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nDC attempted to license &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; as a syndicated [[Comic strip|newspaper strip]] but was unsuccessful.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last = Wells|first = John|title = The Lost DC Kids Line|journal= [[Back Issue!]]|issue = 57|pages = 47|publisher = [[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date = July 2012|location= Raleigh, North Carolina|quote= Did you know that DC tried to sell Shelly Mayer&#39;s &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; as a syndicated newspaper strip? [A] sample, ca. 1979-early 1980s was one of three DC concepts unsuccessfully pitched to papers.}}&lt;/ref&gt; Sales on the \&quot;Sugar and Spike\&quot; issues of &#39;&#39;The Best of DC&#39;&#39; were strong enough that DC announced plans for a new ongoing series featuring the characters.  The project was never launched for unknown reasons.&lt;ref&gt;Wells p. 46-47: \&quot;In a &#39;Meanwhile&#39; column in several Aug. 1984-dated titles...DC vice-president-executive director Dick Giordano tentatively announced &#39;&#39;Sugar and Spike&#39;&#39; #1 as appearing &#39;sometime this fall or early winter&#39;...Ultimately, for reasons virtually no one recalls, DC quickly got cold feet on the project even as Marvel&#39;s Star Comics rolled out in 1985.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nMayer had an agreement with DC that no one else could write Sugar and Spike.&lt;ref name=\&quot;Sugspike\&quot; /&gt; However, they have occasionally made cameo appearances in modern comic books. They are rescued by the underwater heroine [[Dolphin (comics)|Dolphin]] in &#39;&#39;[[Showcase (comics)|Showcase]]&#39;&#39; #100.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|writer= Levitz, Paul; [[Paul Kupperberg|Kupperberg, Paul]]| penciller= [[Joe Staton|Staton, Joe]]|inker= Staton, Joe|story= There Shall Come a Gathering| title= [[Showcase (comics)|Showcase]]|issue= 100|date= May 1978}}&lt;/ref&gt; They appear as theme park characters in &#39;&#39;[[Justice League]] Spectacular&#39;&#39;;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|writer= [[Dan Jurgens|Jurgens, Dan]]; [[Gerard Jones|Jones, Gerard]]|penciller= Jurgens, Dan; [[Ron Randall|Randall, Ron]]| inker= [[Rick Burchett|Burchett, Rick]]; [[Randy Elliot (comics)|Elliot, Randy]]|story= Teamwork|title= [[Justice League|Justice League Spectacular]]|issue= 1|date= March\u2013April 1992}}&lt;/ref&gt; as being baby-sat by [[Wonder Girl|Cassie Sandsmark]] in &#39;&#39;[[Wonder Woman]]&#39;&#39; #113;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|writer= [[John Byrne (comics)|Byrne, John]]|penciller= Byrne, John|inker= Byrne, John|story= Are You Out of Your Minds?!|title= [[Wonder Woman]]|volume= 2|issue= 113|date= September 1996}}&lt;/ref&gt; and as teenagers on the crowded cover of &#39;&#39;[[Legion of Super-Heroes|Legionnaires]]&#39;&#39; #43.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|penciller= [[Jeffrey Moy|Moy, Jeffrey]]|inker= [[W. C. Carani|Carani, W. C.]]|title= [[Legion of Super-Heroes|Legionnaires]]|issue= 43|date= December 1996}}&lt;/ref&gt; They have a cameo on a video screen in Planet Krypton in &#39;&#39;[[Kingdom Come (comic)|Kingdom Come]]&#39;&#39; #1.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic| writer= [[Mark Waid|Waid, Mark]]|penciller= [[Alex Ross|Ross, Alex]]|inker= Ross, Alex|story= Strange Visitor|title= [[Kingdom Come (comic)|Kingdom Come]]|issue= 1|date= May 1996}}&lt;/ref&gt; The two made speaking cameo appearances in the first two pages of &#39;&#39;[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold|The All-New Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]&#39;&#39; #4, but they were not named.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|writer= [[Sholly Fisch|Fisch, Sholly]]|penciller= Burchett, Rick|inker= [[Dan Davis (comics)|Davis, Dan]]|story= The Bride and the Bold| title= [[Batman: The Brave and the Bold|The All-New Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]|issue= 4|date= April 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; In an issue of the digital-first series &#39;&#39;[[Superman (comic book)#Adventures of Superman Volume 2|Adventures of Superman]]&#39;&#39;, the children are babysat by [[Superman]] in his secret identity as reporter Clark Kent.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|writer= [[Fabian Nicieza|Nicieza, Fabian]]|penciller= [[Phil Hester (comics)|Hester, Phil]]|inker= Eric Gapstur|story=The Coming of ... Sugar and Spike --?|title= [[Superman (comic book)#Adventures of Superman Volume 2|Adventures of Superman]]|issue= 42|date=February 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\n==Featured characters==\nThe comic featured the misadventures of two [[toddler]]s named Sugar Plumm and Cecil \&quot;Spike\&quot; Wilson, who possessed the ability to communicate via \&quot;[[baby talk]]\&quot; with each other and to other infants, but not to adults.&lt;ref name=\&quot;Sugspike\&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url= http://www.toonopedia.com/sugspike.htm|title= Sugar and Spike|last= Markstein|first= Don|date= |work= Don Markstein&#39;s Toonopedia|archiveurl= https://archive.today/20120913073710/http://www.toonopedia.com/sugspike.htm|archivedate= September 13, 2012|accessdate= December 13, 2011|quote= Sugar Plumm and Cecil \&quot;Spike\&quot; Wilson had to make sense of their environment without assistance from those who already knew their way around it, because everybody but their fellow babies spoke in the incomprehensible gobbledygook of grownups...[Mayer] secured an agreement with DC that he would be the only one ever to write and draw those characters.|url-status= dead|df= mdy-all}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last = Daniels|first = Les|authorlink = Les Daniels|title = [[DC Comics: Sixty Years of the World&#39;s Favorite Comic Book Heroes]]|chapter= Keep Smiling Having a Sense of Humor Helps|publisher = [[Little, Brown and Company|Bulfinch Press]]|year = 1995|location= New York, New York|page = 240|isbn = 0821220764|quote= The creations of editor and cartoonist Sheldon Mayer, Sugar and Spike were two tiny tots who were old enough to get into trouble but a little too young to talk.  As a result, they conversed in baby talk, &#39;the only language that makes any sense.&#39;}}&lt;/ref&gt; It shared ideas concerning baby-talk with [[P. L. Travers]]&#39; &#39;&#39;[[Mary Poppins (book series)|Mary Poppins]]&#39;&#39; novel; one notable feature was that &#39;&#39;all&#39;&#39; babies spoke the same baby-talk \&quot;language\&quot;, allowing Sugar and Spike to speak with not only human infants, but baby animals as well. Another popular recurring feature was [[paper dolls]] of the two leads, with outfits based on designs submitted by readers. Mayer used his own children, Merrily and Lanney, as inspiration for the strip.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last= Alger|first= Bill|title= Sugar&#39;s Daddy Talking with Merrily Mayer Harris, Shelly Mayer&#39;s Daughter|magazine= [[Comic Book Artist]]|issue= 11|pages= |publisher= TwoMorrows Publishing|date= January 2001|location= Raleigh, North Carolina|url= http://www.twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/11merrily.html|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081119160422/http://www.twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/11merrily.html|archivedate= November 19, 2008|accessdate= May 17, 2012|url-status= dead|df= mdy-all}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nIn addition to the toddlers, their parents and adults, who were only seen from the waist down (Bill and Barbara Plumm; Harvey and Peg Wilson), recurring characters included:\n* &#39;&#39;&#39;Little Arthur&#39;&#39;&#39;, a \&quot;big boy\&quot; too old for baby-talk.  A spoiled brat and a ruffian, Arthur torments Sugar and Spike, but is invariably outwitted by them in the end. He is introduced in issue #17 (August 1958).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|writer= [[Sheldon Mayer|Mayer, Sheldon]]|penciller= Mayer, Sheldon|inker= Mayer, Sheldon|story= Meet Little Arthur|title= Sugar &amp; Spike|issue= 17|date= August 1958}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n* Sugar&#39;s &#39;&#39;&#39;Uncle Charley&#39;&#39;&#39;, a bachelor and police officer who is a stereotypical \&quot;fun uncle\&quot;, often playing with the kids and giving them gifts when he comes to visit.\n*&#39;&#39;&#39;Bernie the Brain&#39;&#39;&#39;, a [[Child prodigy|child genius]] who, despite being the same age as Sugar and Spike, is an accomplished scientist and inventor who speaks and understands \&quot;grown-up talk\&quot;.  When he first encounters Sugar and Spike,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|writer= Mayer, Sheldon|penciller= Mayer, Sheldon|inker= Mayer, Sheldon|story= Bernie the Brain!|title= Sugar &amp; Spike|issue= 72|date= August\u2013September 1967}}&lt;/ref&gt; he requires a translating device of his own invention to teach him their baby-talk having already progressed past that stage, intellectually.  He enjoys the chance to be a normal kid with Sugar and Spike, while the pair loves playing with Bernie&#39;s various inventions.  The two often seek out Bernie when they encounter something they do not understand, particularly something involving grown-up behavior. Bernie made a cameo in &#39;&#39;[[Crisis on Infinite Earths]]&#39;&#39; #9 watching [[Clark Kent]] on the WGBS television news report on the Crisis and he appears to be very concerned about what is going on.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic|writer= [[Marv Wolfman|Wolfman, Marv]]|penciller= [[George P\u00e9rez|P\u00e9rez, George]]|inker= [[Jerry Ordway|Ordway, Jerry]]|story= War Zone|title= [[Crisis on Infinite Earths]]|issue= 9|date= December 1985}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\n==Revival==\nWriter [[Keith Giffen]] and artist Bilquis Evely brought back the characters as adults in 2016,&lt;ref name=newsarama1&gt;{{cite web|url= http://www.newsarama.com/25043-dc-reveals-8-new-limited-series-metal-men-sugar-spike-metamorpho-more.html|title= DC Reveals 8 New Limited Series - &#39;&#39;Metal Men&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;Metamorpho&#39;&#39;, More|first= Chris|last= Arrant|date= July 16, 2015|publisher= Newsarama|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150917214940/http://www.newsarama.com/25043-dc-reveals-8-new-limited-series-metal-men-sugar-spike-metamorpho-more.html|archivedate= September 17, 2015|url-status= dead}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url= http://www.comicbookresources.com/article/didio-shares-first-look-at-giffen-porters-reinvented-sugar-spike|title= DiDio Shares First Look At Giffen &amp; Porter&#39;s Reinvented &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39;|first= Kiel|last= Phegley|date= July 8, 2015|publisher= [[Comic Book Resources]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150905060528/http://www.comicbookresources.com/article/didio-shares-first-look-at-giffen-porters-reinvented-sugar-spike|archivedate= September 5, 2015|url-status= dead}}&lt;/ref&gt; starring their own adventures (among other characters) in the new ongoing series &#39;&#39;Legends of Tomorrow&#39;&#39;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url= http://www.dccomics.com/comics/legends-of-tomorrow-2016/legends-of-tomorrow-1|title= &#39;&#39;Legends of Tomorrow&#39;&#39; #1|date= March 16, 2016|publisher= DC Comics|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160828192434/http://www.dccomics.com/comics/legends-of-tomorrow-2016/legends-of-tomorrow-1|archivedate= August 28, 2016|url-status= live}}&lt;/ref&gt; At the time of the announcement, DC Comics Co-Publisher [[Dan DiDio]] said of the &#39;&#39;Sugar And Spike&#39;&#39; series, \&quot;They&#39;re not spoiled kids anymore, but they&#39;re older and they&#39;re operating as private investigators handling problems and mysteries that the superheroes can&#39;t handle themselves\&quot;.&lt;ref name=newsarama1/&gt;\n\n==In other media==\n*Sugar and Spike have a cameo in the &#39;&#39;[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]&#39;&#39; episode \&quot;The Siege of Starro: Part 1.\&quot; The characters are pictured on the side of an \&quot;S &amp; S Diapers\&quot; diaper service truck.\n*Sugar and Spike are among many other DC characters included in &#39;&#39;[[Scribblenauts Unmasked: A DC Comics Adventure]].&#39;&#39;\n\n==Collected editions==\n* &#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;[[DC Archive Editions|The Sugar and Spike Archives]]&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39; Vol. 1 collects &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39; #1\u201310, 272 pages, September 2011, {{ISBN|1-4012-3112-8}}&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url= http://www.dccomics.com/graphic-novels/sugar-and-spike-archives-vol-1|title= &#39;&#39;The Sugar and Spike Archives&#39;&#39; Vol. 1|publisher= DC Comics|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151113051917/http://www.dccomics.com/graphic-novels/sugar-and-spike-archives-vol-1|archivedate= November 13, 2015|url-status= live|accessdate= October 14, 2012}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n* &#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;The TOON Treasury of Classic Children&#39;s Comics&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39; includes \&quot;Once upon a time there was a cute little baby boy named (of all things) Cecil...\&quot; from &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39; #1; \&quot;Grown-Up Game\&quot; from &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39; #20; and \&quot;Pint-Size Love Story\&quot; from &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39; #21, 360 pages, September 2009, [[Abrams Books|Harry N. Abrams]], {{ISBN|0810957302}}\n* &#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;The Greatest 1950s Stories Ever Told&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39; includes \&quot;Lobsters Away\&quot; from &#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike&#39;&#39; #3, 288 pages, October 1990, {{ISBN|0930289803}}\n* &#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;Sugar &amp; Spike: Metahuman Investigations&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39